        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 28-year-old male with upper respiratory infection symptoms for 4 days. Reports nasal congestion, runny nose (clear to yellow discharge), sore throat, cough (non-productive). No fever. Mild fatigue. Symptoms started gradually. No sick contacts known. No shortness of breath, chest pain, or wheezing. Previously healthy. States: \"I always need antibiotics when I get like this\" and requesting Z-pack.\n\nPast Medical History: None\nMedications: None\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Software engineer, non-smoker, no drug use\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs:\n- BP: 118/72 mmHg\n- HR: 72 bpm\n- Temperature: 98.6\u00b0F (afebrile)\n- RR: 16\n- SpO2: 99% on room air\n\nGeneral: Well-appearing, no acute distress\n\nHEENT:\n- Ears: TMs clear bilaterally\n- Nose: Erythematous turbinates, clear to mucopurulent discharge\n- Throat: Mild pharyngeal erythema, no exudates, no tonsillar enlargement\n- No cervical lymphadenopathy\n\nPulmonary: Clear to auscultation bilaterally, no wheezes, no crackles\n\nCentor Score (for strep pharyngitis): 0\n- No fever\n- No tonsillar exudates\n- No tender anterior cervical nodes\n- Age 28 (no points)\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Acute Viral Upper Respiratory Infection (Common Cold) (ICD-10: J06.9)\n\nClinical Reasoning:\n- Classic URI symptoms: Congestion, rhinorrhea, sore throat, cough\n- Afebrile\n- No signs of bacterial infection (no fever, no exudates, clear lungs)\n- Centor score 0 - strep unlikely\n- Duration 4 days - typical for viral URI (peaks days 3-4, resolves in 7-10 days)\n\nAntibiotics NOT Indicated:\n- Viral infection - antibiotics ineffective\n- No evidence of bacterial superinfection\n- Yellow/green discharge does NOT indicate bacterial infection\n\n### Plan\nEducation on Viral URI:\n\n1. This is a viral infection (common cold)\n2. Antibiotics do NOT work against viruses\n3. Antibiotics have risks: Allergic reactions, diarrhea, C. diff, antibiotic resistance\n4. Natural course: Symptoms peak days 3-4, improve over 7-10 days\n5. Yellow/green mucus is normal in viral infections (not an indication for antibiotics)\n\nSymptomatic Treatment:\n\n6. Hydration: Drink plenty of fluids (water, tea, broth)\n7. Rest: Allow body to recover\n8. Nasal congestion:\n   - Saline nasal spray/rinse (NeilMed, Neti pot) - very effective\n   - Pseudoephedrine (Sudafed) 30-60 mg q4-6h PRN (if no HTN)\n   - Oxymetazoline nasal spray (Afrin) - max 3 days (rebound congestion)\n9. Sore throat:\n   - Salt water gargles\n   - Lozenges (Cepacol, Chloraseptic)\n   - Acetaminophen or ibuprofen for pain\n10. Cough:\n    - Honey (1-2 tsp PRN) - evidence-based\n    - Dextromethorphan (Delsym) if needed\n    - Avoid codeine cough suppressants\n11. Fever/pain: Acetaminophen 650 mg q6h PRN or ibuprofen 400 mg q6h PRN\n\nReturn Precautions (May Indicate Bacterial Infection):\n\n12. Return or seek care if:\n    - Fever >101.3\u00b0F\n    - Symptoms worsening after 7-10 days (or improve then worsen)\n    - Severe sore throat with difficulty swallowing\n    - Shortness of breath, wheezing\n    - Facial pain/pressure with fever (sinusitis)\n    - Ear pain\n    - Neck stiffness\n\nWork/School:\n\n13. Can work if feeling up to it\n14. Practice good hand hygiene\n15. Cover coughs/sneezes\n16. Most contagious first 2-3 days\n\nNo Prescription Needed:\n\n17. No antibiotics prescribed\n18. All recommended treatments are OTC\n\nPatient Response:\n\n19. Explained rationale for not prescribing antibiotics\n20. Patient understands and accepts symptomatic treatment\n21. Will return if worsening or not improving in 10 days"
