        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 45-year-old female with low back pain for 2 weeks. No trauma or specific injury. Pain started gradually, possibly after prolonged sitting during road trip. Describes pain as dull aching in lower back (6/10), with shooting pain down left leg to calf (7/10). Leg pain worse than back pain. Worse with sitting, bending forward, coughing/sneezing. Better lying down, walking. No bowel or bladder dysfunction. No saddle anesthesia. No weakness noticed. No fever, no weight loss.\n\nRed Flag Screening: Negative\n- No trauma\n- No fever/infection signs\n- No cancer history\n- No bowel/bladder dysfunction\n- No progressive weakness\n- No saddle anesthesia\n\nPast Medical History: Obesity, otherwise healthy\nMedications: None regular\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Office manager (sitting job), non-smoker, no exercise program\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs: BP 128/78, HR 72, Weight 195 lbs, Height 5'6\", BMI 31.5\n\nGeneral: Appears uncomfortable, guards back with movement\n\nLumbar Spine:\n- Inspection: Normal lordosis, no deformity\n- ROM: Limited flexion by pain, extension mildly limited\n- Palpation: Paraspinal muscle tenderness L > R, no midline tenderness\n- SLR (Straight Leg Raise): Positive left at 45\u00b0 (reproduces leg pain)\n- SLR right: Negative\n- Crossed SLR: Negative\n\nNeurological:\n- Strength: 5/5 bilateral LE (hip flexion, knee extension, ankle DF/PF, great toe extension)\n- Sensation: Intact L4-S1 bilaterally\n- Reflexes: 2+ patellar, 2+ Achilles bilaterally\n- Gait: Mildly antalgic, no foot drop\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Acute Low Back Pain with Left Lumbar Radiculopathy (Sciatica) (ICD-10: M54.5, M54.31)\n\n- Likely L5 or S1 radiculopathy based on distribution\n- Probable disc herniation causing nerve compression\n- No red flags\n- Neurologically intact\n- Duration: 2 weeks (acute phase)\n\nPrognosis: Good - 90% improve within 6-12 weeks with conservative care\n\n### Plan\nConservative Management (First-Line for Acute Radiculopathy):\n\n1. Activity: Continue normal activities as tolerated\n   - Avoid bed rest (worsens outcomes)\n   - Avoid heavy lifting, prolonged sitting\n   - Walking is encouraged\n\n2. Medications:\n   - NSAIDs: Ibuprofen 600 mg TID with food x 2 weeks (first-line)\n   - Muscle relaxant: Cyclobenzaprine 10 mg at bedtime PRN x 1-2 weeks\n   - GI protection if NSAID sensitive: Omeprazole 20 mg daily\n\n3. Physical Therapy referral:\n   - McKenzie method (directional preference exercises)\n   - Core stabilization\n   - Nerve glides/neural mobilization\n   - Posture and body mechanics\n   - Start within 1-2 weeks\n\n4. Home exercises:\n   - Gentle stretching\n   - Walking program\n   - Avoid forward bending initially\n\n5. Heat/ice: Either can be used for comfort, 15-20 min at a time\n\nNeuropathic Pain (If Needed):\n\n6. If leg pain predominant, can add:\n   - Gabapentin 100-300 mg TID (start low, titrate)\n   - Or pregabalin 50-75 mg BID\n   - Not starting today, try NSAID first\n\nImaging:\n\n7. MRI NOT indicated initially (< 6 weeks, no red flags)\n8. Obtain MRI if:\n   - No improvement after 6 weeks conservative care\n   - Progressive neurological deficit\n   - Red flag symptoms develop\n\nWork Modifications:\n\n9. Office job with prolonged sitting\n   - Stand or walk every 30-60 minutes\n   - Lumbar support cushion\n   - Adjust workstation ergonomics\n   - May need temporary work restrictions if severe\n\nReturn Precautions (Seek Immediate Care If):\n\n10. Cauda equina syndrome signs:\n    - Bowel or bladder incontinence or retention\n    - Saddle anesthesia\n    - Progressive weakness in legs\n    - Bilateral leg symptoms\n11. Fever or signs of infection\n12. Severe worsening pain\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n13. Return in 2-4 weeks if not improving\n14. Call sooner if worsening or red flags\n15. Most patients improve significantly in 4-6 weeks\n\nWeight Management:\n\n16. BMI 31.5 - weight contributes to back pain\n17. Discuss weight loss strategies\n18. Once acute pain resolved, start exercise program\n\nEducation:\n\n19. Reassurance: Most sciatica resolves without surgery\n20. Staying active is better than bed rest\n21. Pain does not equal damage - movement is medicine\n22. Recovery may take weeks but is expected"
