        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 62-year-old male presenting with chest pain for past 2 weeks. Describes substernal pressure/tightness, 6/10 severity, occurring with exertion (walking uphill, climbing stairs, carrying groceries). Pain radiates to left arm. Associated with mild shortness of breath. Relieved by rest within 5 minutes. No pain at rest currently. No nausea, vomiting, diaphoresis with episodes. Episodes last 3-5 minutes. Occurring 3-4 times per week, predictable with exertion. No recent change in frequency or intensity.\n\nCardiac Risk Factors:\n- Hypertension x 15 years\n- Hyperlipidemia x 10 years\n- Type 2 diabetes x 8 years\n- Smoking: Quit 5 years ago (30 pack-years)\n- Family history: Father MI at 55, brother stent at 52\n- Sedentary lifestyle\n\nPast Medical History:\n- HTN, DM2, HLD\n- No prior cardiac history\n- No prior stress test or catheterization\n\nMedications:\n- Lisinopril 20 mg daily\n- Metformin 1000 mg BID\n- Atorvastatin 40 mg daily\n- Aspirin 81 mg daily\n\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Retired, former smoker, no alcohol\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs:\n- BP: 142/88 mmHg\n- HR: 78 bpm\n- RR: 16\n- SpO2: 98% on RA\n- Weight: 220 lbs, BMI: 31\n\nGeneral: Alert, comfortable, no acute distress (currently pain-free)\n\nCardiovascular:\n- Regular rate and rhythm\n- S1, S2 normal, no S3/S4\n- No murmurs\n- JVP not elevated\n- Peripheral pulses 2+ bilaterally\n- No peripheral edema\n\nPulmonary: Clear to auscultation\n\nAbdomen: Soft, obese, non-tender\n\nECG (done today): Normal sinus rhythm, no ST changes, no Q waves, no ischemic changes at rest\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Typical Angina Pectoris - Probable Stable Angina (ICD-10: I20.9)\n\nAngina Classification:\n- Substernal chest discomfort\n- Provoked by exertion\n- Relieved by rest\n- All 3 criteria = TYPICAL ANGINA\n\nPre-Test Probability of CAD: HIGH\n- Male, age 62\n- Typical angina symptoms\n- Multiple cardiac risk factors (HTN, DM, HLD, smoking history, strong FHx)\n\nRisk Stratification: Intermediate-high risk - needs evaluation\n\n### Plan\nImmediate Management:\n\n1. Start antianginal therapy:\n   - Aspirin 81 mg daily - CONTINUE\n   - Atorvastatin: Increase to 80 mg daily (high-intensity statin)\n   - ADD: Nitroglycerin 0.4 mg SL PRN for chest pain (carry at all times)\n   - ADD: Metoprolol succinate 25 mg daily (beta-blocker for angina)\n\n2. Nitroglycerin instructions:\n   - Take 1 tablet under tongue at onset of chest pain\n   - May repeat every 5 minutes x 3 doses\n   - If pain persists after 3 doses: CALL 911\n   - Sit down before taking (can cause hypotension)\n   - Store in original container, check expiration\n\nCardiac Workup:\n\n3. Labs:\n   - Troponin (today) - rule out acute event\n   - BNP\n   - Lipid panel\n   - HbA1c\n   - BMP\n   - CBC\n\n4. Stress Testing (URGENT - within 1-2 weeks):\n   - Exercise stress test with imaging (stress echo or nuclear)\n   - If unable to exercise: Pharmacologic stress (adenosine, regadenoson, dobutamine)\n   - Will reveal if ischemia present and extent\n\n5. If positive stress test:\n   - Cardiology referral\n   - Likely coronary angiography\n   - Discussion of revascularization (PCI vs CABG)\n\n6. Cardiology referral: Urgent if symptoms worsen, otherwise after stress test\n\nRisk Factor Optimization:\n\n7. Blood pressure: 142/88 - not at goal\n   - Start metoprolol (above) - helps BP and angina\n   - Goal BP: <130/80\n   - May need to increase lisinopril if not at goal\n\n8. Diabetes: A1c likely elevated\n   - Goal A1c <7%\n   - Continue metformin, add medication if needed\n   - Consider SGLT2 inhibitor (cardiovascular benefit)\n\n9. Lipids: Increase statin to high-intensity\n   - Goal LDL <70 mg/dL (with CAD)\n   - Consider adding ezetimibe if not at goal\n\n10. Smoking: Quit 5 years - excellent, continue abstinence\n\n11. Weight: BMI 31 - discuss weight loss\n    - Goal: Lose 10% body weight\n    - Cardiac rehab can help after workup complete\n\nActivity Precautions:\n\n12. Avoid strenuous exertion that triggers symptoms until workup complete\n13. Light activity okay\n14. Use nitroglycerin if chest pain occurs\n15. Call 911 if chest pain at rest, prolonged, or severe\n\nRed Flags - Go to ER Immediately:\n\n16. Chest pain at rest lasting >20 minutes\n17. Chest pain not relieved by nitroglycerin\n18. Chest pain with diaphoresis, nausea, severe SOB\n19. Chest pain with syncope\n20. Any change in pattern (more frequent, more severe, longer lasting = unstable angina)\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n21. Stress test scheduled within 1-2 weeks\n22. Call with results\n23. If positive: Cardiology referral for angiography\n24. Return visit in 2-4 weeks to review results and optimize medications\n25. Call or ER if worsening symptoms\n\nPatient Education:\n\n26. Symptoms are consistent with angina (reduced blood flow to heart)\n27. Need to determine if blockages present\n28. Treatable with medications, stents, or surgery depending on findings\n29. Importance of risk factor control\n30. Carry nitroglycerin at all times"
