        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is an 8-year-old male brought by mother with sore throat for 2 days. Reports throat pain rated 6/10, worse with swallowing. Fever at home (102\u00b0F last night), given ibuprofen with improvement. Decreased appetite due to throat pain. No cough. No runny nose. No rash. No abdominal pain, nausea, or vomiting. Friend at school diagnosed with strep last week. No recent URI symptoms. Drinking adequate fluids.\n\nPast Medical History: Healthy, no chronic conditions\nMedications: Ibuprofen PRN for fever\nAllergies: NKDA\nImmunizations: Up to date\nSocial: 2nd grade, lives with both parents, has younger sibling\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs:\n- Temp: 101.2\u00b0F (38.4\u00b0C)\n- HR: 98 bpm\n- Weight: 58 lbs (26 kg)\n\nGeneral: Alert, mildly ill-appearing, cooperative\n\nHEENT:\n- Ears: TMs clear bilaterally\n- Nose: No rhinorrhea, no congestion\n- Throat: Pharyngeal erythema with tonsillar enlargement (2+), white-yellow exudates on tonsils bilaterally\n- Palatal petechiae: Present\n- Uvula: Midline, not swollen\n\nNeck: Tender anterior cervical lymphadenopathy bilaterally (1-2 cm nodes)\n\nCardiovascular: Regular rate, no murmur\n\nPulmonary: Clear to auscultation, no cough during exam\n\nSkin: No rash (no scarlet fever rash)\n\nAbdomen: Soft, non-tender\n\nCentor/McIsaac Score:\n- Fever (\u226538\u00b0C): +1\n- Absence of cough: +1\n- Tonsillar exudates: +1\n- Tender anterior cervical nodes: +1\n- Age 3-14: +1\n- **Total: 5 points (HIGH probability of strep)**\n\nRapid Strep Test: POSITIVE\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Group A Streptococcal Pharyngitis (Strep Throat) (ICD-10: J02.0)\n\nConfirmed by positive rapid strep test with classic clinical presentation.\n\n### Plan\nAntibiotic Treatment:\n\n1. Amoxicillin 500 mg PO BID x 10 days (weight-based dosing for 26 kg child: 50 mg/kg/day = ~650 mg BID, but 500 mg BID is practical and effective)\n   - Alternative dosing: Amoxicillin 25-50 mg/kg/day divided BID or TID\n   - Prescribed: Amoxicillin 500 mg BID (or TID if preferred) x 10 days\n\n2. If penicillin allergic:\n   - Cephalexin 20 mg/kg/dose BID (if not anaphylactic to PCN)\n   - Azithromycin 12 mg/kg day 1, then 6 mg/kg days 2-5 (if anaphylactic)\n   - Clindamycin if multiple allergies\n\n3. Complete FULL 10-day course even if feeling better\n   - Prevents rheumatic fever, suppurative complications\n   - Prevents spread to others\n\nSymptomatic Treatment:\n\n4. Ibuprofen (Advil/Motrin): 10 mg/kg every 6-8 hours PRN for pain/fever\n   - ~260 mg per dose (can use 200-300 mg)\n5. Acetaminophen (Tylenol): 15 mg/kg every 4-6 hours PRN (alternative)\n   - ~400 mg per dose\n6. Encourage fluids: Cold drinks, popsicles, soft foods\n7. Salt water gargles (if able)\n8. Throat lozenges (age-appropriate, avoid choking hazard)\n9. Cool mist humidifier at night\n\nContagion Precautions:\n\n10. Contagious until on antibiotics for 24 hours\n11. May return to school after 24 hours of antibiotics AND fever-free\n12. Expected return to school: 2 days from now\n13. Replace toothbrush after 24 hours of treatment (prevents reinfection)\n14. Monitor family members for symptoms\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n15. Should improve within 24-48 hours of starting antibiotics\n16. Throat culture NOT needed (rapid strep positive)\n17. Return if:\n    - Not improving after 48 hours\n    - Fever persists >3 days on antibiotics\n    - Difficulty swallowing or breathing\n    - Drooling, voice changes\n    - Neck stiffness or swelling\n    - Rash develops (may be scarlet fever - still treat with same antibiotics)\n\nComplications to Watch For:\n\n18. Peritonsillar abscess: Severe unilateral throat pain, trismus, voice changes, drooling\n19. Rheumatic fever: Prevented by completing antibiotics (rare if treated)\n20. PSGN (post-strep glomerulonephritis): Dark urine, facial swelling (antibiotics don't prevent this, but self-limited)\n\nPatient/Parent Education:\n\n21. Strep throat is bacterial infection requiring antibiotics\n22. Untreated strep can lead to complications (rheumatic fever, kidney problems)\n23. Must complete 10-day course\n24. Expect improvement in 1-2 days\n25. Stay home until 24 hours on antibiotics and fever-free"
