        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 70-year-old female presenting with memory concerns for approximately 1 year, gradually worsening. Reports forgetting names of acquaintances, missing appointments, repeating questions, difficulty finding words. Brought list of concerns (good insight). Daughter accompanies and confirms observations. Patient still manages medications independently with pillbox, handles finances with husband's help, drives locally (no accidents), prepares meals. Concerned about dementia given family history (mother had Alzheimer's at 78). Denies getting lost in familiar places. No hallucinations. Sleep okay. Mood slightly anxious about memory.\n\nFunctional Status:\n- IADLs: Mostly independent\n- Medications: Independent with pillbox\n- Finances: Some help from husband\n- Driving: Independent locally\n- Cooking: Independent\n- No safety concerns reported\n\nPast Medical History:\n- Hypertension\n- Hyperlipidemia\n- Hypothyroidism\n- Osteoporosis\n\nMedications:\n- Lisinopril 10 mg daily\n- Atorvastatin 20 mg daily\n- Levothyroxine 75 mcg daily\n- Alendronate 70 mg weekly\n- Calcium/Vitamin D\n\nAllergies: Sulfa (rash)\nFamily History: Mother - Alzheimer's disease at 78\nSocial: Retired teacher, lives with husband, non-smoker, no alcohol\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs:\n- BP: 134/78 mmHg\n- HR: 72 bpm\n- Weight: 145 lbs\n\nGeneral: Well-groomed, pleasant, cooperative, good historian with some word-finding pauses\n\nNeurological:\n- Alert, oriented to person, place, date\n- Speech: Fluent with occasional word-finding difficulty\n- Cranial nerves: Intact\n- Motor: 5/5 throughout\n- Sensation: Intact\n- Reflexes: 2+ symmetric\n- Gait: Normal\n- No parkinsonism (no tremor, rigidity, bradykinesia)\n\nCognitive Screening:\n- MMSE (Mini-Mental State Exam): 26/30\n  - Lost points: Delayed recall (2 points), attention/calculation (1 point), sentence writing (1 point)\n- MoCA (if done): Typically more sensitive for MCI\n\nMood: PHQ-2: 1 (negative screen)\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Mild Cognitive Impairment (MCI), Likely Amnestic Type (ICD-10: F06.7)\n\nClinical Reasoning:\n- Subjective memory complaints confirmed by informant\n- Objective cognitive impairment on testing (MMSE 26, memory domain affected)\n- Functional abilities largely preserved\n- Does not meet criteria for dementia (IADLs intact)\n\nDifferential Diagnosis:\n- MCI (most likely) - may progress to Alzheimer's disease\n- Early Alzheimer's disease\n- Vascular cognitive impairment\n- Depression (pseudodementia) - less likely, not depressed\n- Hypothyroidism - currently treated\n- Vitamin B12 deficiency\n- Normal aging - less likely given objective impairment\n\n### Plan\nDiagnostic Workup:\n\n1. Labs to rule out reversible causes:\n   - CBC\n   - CMP (including glucose, kidney function)\n   - TSH (already on levothyroxine, ensure adequately treated)\n   - Vitamin B12 level\n   - Folate\n   - Consider: RPR, HIV (if risk factors)\n\n2. Brain Imaging:\n   - MRI brain without contrast (preferred)\n   - Evaluate for: Atrophy pattern, vascular disease, masses, hydrocephalus\n   - Alternative: CT head if MRI contraindicated\n\n3. Neuropsychological Testing:\n   - Referral for formal testing\n   - Detailed cognitive profile (memory, language, executive function, visuospatial)\n   - Helps distinguish MCI from early dementia\n   - Establishes baseline for monitoring\n\n4. Consider Neurology referral for comprehensive evaluation\n\nTreatment:\n\n5. Currently NO medication indicated for MCI:\n   - Cholinesterase inhibitors (donepezil, etc.) NOT proven effective for MCI\n   - May consider if progresses to dementia\n\n6. Lifestyle Interventions (Evidence-Based):\n   - Physical exercise: Aerobic activity 150 min/week (walking, swimming)\n   - Cognitive stimulation: Puzzles, reading, new learning, social engagement\n   - Mediterranean or MIND diet\n   - Adequate sleep (7-8 hours)\n   - Social engagement: Stay active with friends, family, groups\n\n7. Cardiovascular Risk Factor Control:\n   - HTN: BP 134/78 - reasonable, but aim for <130/80\n   - Cholesterol: Continue statin\n   - Avoid smoking, limit alcohol\n   - Control diabetes if present\n\nSafety Assessment:\n\n8. Driving: Currently safe (local only, no accidents)\n   - Monitor for decline\n   - Formal driving evaluation if concerns arise\n9. Medication management: Currently okay with pillbox\n10. No need for supervision currently\n11. Financial oversight: Husband helping - appropriate\n\nAdvance Care Planning:\n\n12. Good time to discuss:\n    - Healthcare proxy/Power of Attorney\n    - Living will/advance directives\n    - While patient has capacity to participate\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n13. Return in 6-12 months for cognitive reassessment\n14. Sooner if noticeable decline\n15. Track functional status over time\n16. Repeat cognitive testing annually to monitor for progression\n\nMCI Progression:\n\n17. MCI progresses to dementia at rate of ~10-15% per year\n18. Some remain stable, few revert to normal\n19. Early intervention and monitoring important\n\nPatient/Family Education:\n\n20. MCI is not dementia - function is preserved\n21. Does increase risk for future dementia\n22. No proven medication, but lifestyle matters\n23. Close monitoring recommended\n24. Resources: Alzheimer's Association for information and support\n\nReferrals:\n\n25. Neuropsychology for formal testing\n26. Neurology (optional, depending on results)\n27. Brain MRI ordered"
