        "input": "58yo M diabetic presents numbness tingling feet. neuropathy suspected. needs eval management. \u0394 diabetic peripheral neuropathy",
        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 58-year-old male with type 2 diabetes presenting with numbness and tingling in both feet for 6 months, gradually worsening. Describes \"pins and needles\" sensation and \"walking on cotton.\" Worse at night. Occasional burning pain. Symptoms started in toes, now to mid-foot. No back pain, no leg weakness. Balance slightly worse. Has had diabetes for 12 years, A1c running 8-9% (not well controlled). No prior evaluation for neuropathy.\n\nSymptoms:\n- Numbness/tingling bilateral feet (symmetric)\n- Burning pain intermittent, 4/10\n- Worse at night\n- Ascending pattern (started toes, now feet)\n- No motor symptoms\n\nPast Medical History:\n- Type 2 diabetes x 12 years (A1c 8.5%)\n- Hypertension\n- Hyperlipidemia\n- Obesity\n\nMedications:\n- Metformin 1000 mg BID\n- Glipizide 10 mg daily\n- Lisinopril 20 mg daily\n- Atorvastatin 40 mg daily\n\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Non-smoker, occasional alcohol, sedentary job (truck driver)\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs:\n- BP: 138/82 mmHg\n- HR: 76 bpm\n- Weight: 245 lbs, BMI: 34\n\nGeneral: Obese male, comfortable\n\nNeurological Examination:\n- Motor: 5/5 strength bilateral LE (hip flexion, knee extension, ankle DF/PF, toe extension)\n- Sensation:\n  - Light touch: Diminished bilateral feet (to ankle level)\n  - Pinprick: Diminished bilateral feet\n  - Vibration (128 Hz tuning fork): Absent at great toe, diminished at ankle\n  - Proprioception: Mildly impaired at toes\n  - Monofilament (10g): Unable to feel at multiple sites on plantar feet bilaterally\n- Reflexes: Ankle reflexes absent bilaterally, knee reflexes 1+\n- Gait: Mildly wide-based, Romberg positive\n\nFoot Examination:\n- Skin: Dry, calluses on pressure points\n- Pulses: Dorsalis pedis 1+ bilateral, posterior tibial 1+ bilateral\n- No ulcers, no deformities\n- No hair growth on feet (suggestive of vascular/neuropathy)\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Diabetic Peripheral Neuropathy (DPN) - Distal Symmetric Polyneuropathy (ICD-10: E11.42)\n\nCriteria Met:\n- Diabetic patient with neuropathy symptoms\n- Symmetric, distal, length-dependent pattern\n- Sensory predominant (numbness, tingling, pain)\n- Objective sensory loss on examination\n- Absent ankle reflexes\n\nPoor Glycemic Control Contributing:\n- A1c 8.5% (goal <7%)\n- 12-year diabetes duration\n\nComplications/Risks:\n- Fall risk (impaired proprioception, positive Romberg)\n- Foot ulcer risk (cannot feel monofilament)\n- Charcot foot risk\n\n### Plan\nGlycemic Control (Most Important Intervention):\n\n1. Intensify diabetes management:\n   - Target A1c <7%\n   - Current: Metformin + glipizide - inadequate control\n   - ADD: Semaglutide (Ozempic) 0.25 mg weekly, titrate up\n   - Alternative: Add basal insulin or SGLT2 inhibitor\n2. Endocrinology referral for diabetes optimization\n3. Diabetes education, nutrition counseling\n4. Improved control slows/prevents progression of neuropathy\n\nNeuropathic Pain Management:\n\n5. First-line options:\n   - Duloxetine 30 mg daily, increase to 60 mg after 1-2 weeks\n   - OR Gabapentin 300 mg at bedtime, titrate to 300 mg TID\n   - OR Pregabalin 50 mg BID, titrate to 150-300 mg BID\n6. Starting: Gabapentin 100 mg at bedtime, increase by 100 mg every 3-7 days to 300 mg TID as tolerated\n7. Topical option: Capsaicin 0.075% cream applied to feet QID (wash hands after)\n8. Lidocaine 5% patch to feet (can use up to 3 patches, 12 hours on/12 hours off)\n\nFoot Care (CRITICAL):\n\n9. Daily foot inspection (patient or family member)\n10. Check between toes, soles, heels\n11. Use mirror if needed\n12. Report any cuts, blisters, color changes, swelling immediately\n13. Moisturize feet daily (not between toes)\n14. Proper footwear:\n    - Diabetic shoes with custom insoles (covered by Medicare)\n    - Never walk barefoot\n    - Check inside shoes for objects before wearing\n15. Nail care: Podiatry referral for nail trimming\n16. Podiatry referral for comprehensive diabetic foot care\n\nFall Prevention:\n\n17. Positive Romberg, proprioceptive loss = fall risk\n18. Precautions:\n    - Nightlight to bathroom\n    - Remove throw rugs\n    - Handrails on stairs\n    - Use caution in dark\n19. Physical therapy referral for balance training, gait stability\n20. Assess need for assistive device if worsening\n\nAdditional Evaluation:\n\n21. Labs:\n    - A1c (confirm current level)\n    - B12 level (metformin can cause deficiency, which worsens neuropathy)\n    - TSH (hypothyroidism can cause neuropathy)\n    - CBC, CMP\n    - Lipid panel\n22. If B12 low: Supplement 1000 mcg daily\n23. EMG/Nerve conduction studies: Consider if atypical features or rapid progression\n    - Supports diagnosis but not required if classic presentation\n\nCardiovascular Risk:\n\n24. Diabetic neuropathy indicates microvascular disease\n25. Optimize:\n    - BP goal <130/80\n    - LDL goal <70\n    - Continue statin, ACE inhibitor\n    - Aspirin 81 mg daily for cardiovascular protection\n26. Screen for other complications:\n    - Diabetic retinopathy: Annual eye exam\n    - Diabetic nephropathy: Urine microalbumin\n\nLifestyle:\n\n27. Weight loss: BMI 34 - goal lose 10% body weight\n28. Exercise: Improves glucose control and circulation\n    - Walking, swimming (non-weight bearing if balance issues)\n29. Smoking: Non-smoker - excellent\n30. Alcohol: Limit (can worsen neuropathy)\n\nWork Consideration:\n\n31. Patient is truck driver\n32. Must monitor for worsening symptoms\n33. Neuropathy can affect ability to feel pedals\n34. May need CDL medical review if progresses\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n35. Return in 4-6 weeks to assess:\n    - Pain control\n    - Medication tolerance\n    - Glucose control\n36. Podiatry: Within 2-4 weeks\n37. Endocrinology referral\n38. Ophthalmology: Annual diabetic eye exam\n39. Labs before next visit\n\nPatient Education:\n\n40. Neuropathy is caused by diabetes and high blood sugars\n41. Controlling blood sugar can slow or prevent worsening\n42. Cannot restore lost sensation, but can prevent progression\n43. Foot care is critical - prevent ulcers and amputations\n44. Medications can help pain but work gradually"
