        "input": "42yo F presents insomnia 3mo. cant fall asleep. stress work. no sleep aids tried. \u0394 chronic insomnia evaluation",
        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 42-year-old female presenting with insomnia for 3 months. Reports difficulty falling asleep - lies in bed 1-2 hours before falling asleep. Sleep latency: 60-90 minutes (normal <30 min). Wakes up tired, not refreshed. Occasional middle-of-night awakening but main issue is sleep onset. Getting 4-5 hours of sleep per night (needs 7-8). Daytime fatigue, difficulty concentrating at work, irritability. Symptoms started when took new job with increased responsibility. Worried about sleep - \"clock watching\" in bed. Uses phone in bed. Drinks coffee throughout day (last cup around 4 PM). No snoring per partner, no witnessed apneas. No restless legs.\n\nSleep History:\n- Bedtime: 10 PM (but lies awake until midnight)\n- Wake time: 6 AM\n- Time in bed: 8 hours\n- Actual sleep: 4-5 hours\n- Sleep efficiency: ~50-60% (poor)\n- Naps: Occasionally on weekends\n- No previous sleep problems until 3 months ago\n\nHabits:\n- Caffeine: 3-4 cups coffee/day, last at 4 PM\n- Alcohol: Glass of wine with dinner sometimes (thinks it helps sleep)\n- Screen time: Phone in bed until tries to sleep\n- Exercise: Minimal\n\nPast Medical History: Anxiety (mild, untreated), otherwise healthy\nMedications: Multivitamin\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Marketing manager, high stress job, lives with partner, no children\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs:\n- BP: 122/76 mmHg\n- HR: 74 bpm\n- Weight: 148 lbs\n\nGeneral: Appears tired, dark circles under eyes, otherwise well\n\nPsychiatric:\n- Mood: \"Stressed\"\n- Affect: Anxious\n- PHQ-9: 6 (mild)\n- GAD-7: 10 (moderate anxiety)\n\nPhysical Exam: Unremarkable, neck circumference normal, oropharynx normal (no signs of sleep apnea)\n\nEpworth Sleepiness Scale: 8 (normal <10)\n\nInsomnia Severity Index (ISI): 18 (moderate-severe insomnia)\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Chronic Insomnia Disorder (ICD-10: G47.00)\n\nCriteria Met:\n- Difficulty initiating sleep\n- >3 months duration\n- Adequate opportunity for sleep\n- Daytime impairment (fatigue, concentration)\n- Not better explained by other disorder\n\nContributing Factors:\n- Stress/anxiety (work-related)\n- Poor sleep hygiene (caffeine, phone in bed, clock watching)\n- Conditioned arousal (bed = anxiety about not sleeping)\n- Alcohol (disrupts sleep quality)\n\nNo Indication for Sleep Apnea Workup:\n- No snoring, apneas, or high Epworth score\n- Normal BMI and neck circumference\n\n### Plan\nCognitive Behavioral Therapy for Insomnia (CBT-I) - First-Line Treatment:\n\n1. CBT-I is FIRST-LINE treatment for chronic insomnia (more effective and durable than medications)\n2. Referral to sleep psychologist/therapist for formal CBT-I\n3. Alternative: Digital CBT-I programs (Somryst FDA-cleared, or apps like Sleepio)\n4. Components of CBT-I:\n   - Sleep restriction therapy\n   - Stimulus control\n   - Cognitive restructuring\n   - Sleep hygiene education\n   - Relaxation techniques\n\nSleep Hygiene Education (Immediate Implementation):\n\n5. Caffeine: Stop by noon (caffeine half-life 5-6 hours)\n6. Alcohol: Avoid within 3 hours of bedtime (disrupts sleep architecture)\n7. Screen time: No phone/computer 1 hour before bed (blue light suppresses melatonin)\n8. Bedroom: Dark, cool (65-68\u00b0F), quiet, use for sleep and sex only\n9. Clock: Remove or turn away (prevents clock-watching anxiety)\n10. Regular schedule: Same wake time every day, even weekends\n11. Exercise: Regular exercise, but not within 3-4 hours of bedtime\n\nStimulus Control (Key Behavioral Intervention):\n\n12. Go to bed only when sleepy (not just tired)\n13. If unable to sleep after 20 minutes, get out of bed\n14. Go to another room, do quiet activity (reading, not screens)\n15. Return to bed only when sleepy\n16. Repeat as needed\n17. Goal: Reassociate bed with sleep, not frustration\n\nSleep Restriction (Powerful Technique):\n\n18. Limit time in bed to actual sleep time initially\n    - Currently sleeping ~5 hours, spending 8 hours in bed\n    - Restrict to 6 hours in bed initially (e.g., 12 AM - 6 AM)\n19. Creates sleep pressure, improves efficiency\n20. Gradually extend as efficiency improves (>85%)\n21. Formal sleep restriction best done with CBT-I therapist\n\nRelaxation Techniques:\n\n22. Progressive muscle relaxation\n23. Deep breathing exercises (4-7-8 technique)\n24. Mindfulness/meditation apps (Calm, Headspace)\n25. Practice in evening, not just when trying to sleep\n\nAddress Anxiety:\n\n26. GAD-7: 10 - moderate anxiety\n27. Stress management strategies\n28. Consider counseling for work stress\n29. If anxiety significant: May consider SSRI (would help both anxiety and sleep)\n30. Current plan: Start with CBT-I, reassess anxiety\n\nMedications (Second-Line, If CBT-I Insufficient):\n\n31. Not starting sleep medication initially\n32. If needed later, options:\n    - Melatonin 3-5 mg 1 hour before bed (OTC, minimal side effects)\n    - Trazodone 25-50 mg at bedtime (off-label, sedating antidepressant)\n    - Low-dose doxepin 3-6 mg (Silenor)\n    - Avoid benzodiazepines and Z-drugs long-term (dependence, rebound insomnia)\n33. Discuss risks/benefits if not improving with CBT-I\n\nSleep Diary:\n\n34. Keep sleep diary for 2 weeks:\n    - Bedtime, sleep latency, wake times, total sleep\n    - Caffeine, alcohol, medications\n    - How rested felt in morning (1-10)\n35. Bring to follow-up\n\nWork-up (Not Indicated Currently):\n\n36. Sleep study (polysomnography): Not needed unless symptoms of sleep apnea, restless legs, or no response to treatment\n37. Labs: Consider TSH if other symptoms of thyroid disorder\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n38. Return in 4-6 weeks to assess:\n    - Sleep diary review\n    - Response to sleep hygiene/behavioral changes\n    - CBT-I progress\n    - Anxiety\n39. Consider medication if not improving with behavioral therapy\n\nPatient Education:\n\n40. Insomnia is treatable\n41. CBT-I is more effective long-term than sleeping pills\n42. Takes time and consistency - not overnight fix\n43. Medication is option but not first choice for chronic insomnia\n44. Addressing stress/anxiety will help sleep"
