        "input": "22yo F presents acne moderate. tried OTC failed. wants prescription. \u0394 acne vulgaris treatment",
        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 22-year-old female presenting with acne for 3 years. Currently moderate severity with mix of comedones and inflammatory papules/pustules. Located on face (cheeks, chin, forehead) and some on upper back. Has tried OTC products (benzoyl peroxide wash, salicylic acid) with minimal improvement. Breakouts worse around menstrual period. Occasional scarring from picking. Affecting self-esteem and confidence. No current prescription treatments. Not currently pregnant, sexually active, uses oral contraceptives.\n\nSkin Care Routine:\n- Cleanser: Salicylic acid wash\n- Moisturizer: Yes, oil-free\n- Sunscreen: Sometimes\n- Makeup: Daily, removes at night\n\nPast Medical History: None\nMedications: Oral contraceptive (Sprintec) x 2 years\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: College student, non-smoker, social alcohol\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs: BP 118/72, Weight 135 lbs\n\nSkin Examination:\n- Face:\n  - Distribution: Bilateral cheeks, chin, forehead\n  - Comedones: Multiple open and closed comedones\n  - Papules: 15-20 inflammatory papules\n  - Pustules: 8-10 pustules\n  - Nodules/cysts: None (no severe/nodulocystic acne)\n  - Scarring: Few shallow atrophic scars on cheeks\n  - Post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation: Present\n- Upper back: Scattered comedones and few papules\n- Chest: Clear\n\nAcne Grade: Moderate inflammatory acne\n\nHirsutism: None\nSigns of hyperandrogenism: None\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Acne Vulgaris, Moderate (ICD-10: L70.0)\n\n- Moderate inflammatory acne with comedonal component\n- Failed OTC benzoyl peroxide and salicylic acid alone\n- No nodules/cysts (not severe)\n- Some post-inflammatory hyperpigmentation and early scarring\n- Menstrual flares suggest hormonal component\n\n### Plan\nTopical Therapy (First-Line for Moderate Acne):\n\n1. Combination topical therapy - more effective than single agents:\n   - Adapalene 0.1%/Benzoyl peroxide 2.5% gel (Epiduo) - apply to face nightly\n   - OR Tretinoin 0.025% cream nightly + Benzoyl peroxide 5% gel in morning\n\n2. Prescribed: Adapalene 0.1% gel (Differin) - apply to entire face nightly\n   - Start every other night for 2 weeks, then nightly\n   - Retinoid = first-line for comedonal and inflammatory acne\n   - Prevents new lesions, treats existing\n   - Expect purging first 2-4 weeks (temporary worsening)\n\n3. Benzoyl peroxide 5% gel - apply in morning\n   - Antibacterial, reduces P. acnes\n   - Can bleach fabrics (use white towels/pillowcases)\n\n4. If not responding in 8-12 weeks, add:\n   - Topical antibiotic: Clindamycin 1% gel (use with benzoyl peroxide to prevent resistance)\n   - Available as combination: Clindamycin/benzoyl peroxide gel (Duac, BenzaClin)\n\nOral Therapy (If Moderate-Severe or Topicals Fail):\n\n5. Not starting oral antibiotics today - try topicals first\n6. If inadequate response at 12 weeks, consider:\n   - Doxycycline 100 mg daily (or 50 mg BID) x 3 months\n   - Limit duration to 3-4 months to minimize resistance\n\nHormonal Therapy:\n\n7. Already on oral contraceptive (Sprintec) - helps acne\n8. If hormonal component prominent:\n   - Could switch to OCP with higher anti-androgen effect (e.g., Yaz, Ortho Tri-Cyclen)\n   - Spironolactone 50-100 mg daily: Anti-androgen, effective for hormonal acne\n   - Consider if ongoing menstrual flares\n\nSkin Care Recommendations:\n\n9. Gentle cleanser: Cetaphil, CeraVe, La Roche-Posay (non-comedogenic)\n10. Moisturizer: Oil-free, non-comedogenic (CeraVe PM, Neutrogena Hydro Boost)\n11. Sunscreen: Daily SPF 30+ (retinoids increase sun sensitivity, also helps hyperpigmentation)\n12. Makeup: Non-comedogenic, remove every night\n13. Avoid picking: Worsens scarring and hyperpigmentation\n\nPost-Inflammatory Hyperpigmentation:\n\n14. Will improve with acne treatment and sun protection\n15. Retinoids help fade hyperpigmentation\n16. Additional options later: Azelaic acid 15-20%, vitamin C serum, chemical peels\n\nRetinoid Instructions:\n\n17. Apply pea-sized amount to entire face, not just spots\n18. Avoid eye area, corners of mouth, nostrils\n19. Start every other night to minimize irritation\n20. Expect dryness, redness, peeling initially - use moisturizer\n21. Takes 8-12 weeks to see full effect - be patient\n22. Use sunscreen daily - increased photosensitivity\n23. Avoid waxing on retinoid (can cause skin tears)\n24. If trying to conceive in future: Stop retinoid (pregnancy category)\n\nScarring:\n\n25. Current scars are mild\n26. Priority: Prevent new acne and scarring\n27. Once acne controlled, can consider:\n    - Chemical peels\n    - Microneedling\n    - Laser treatments\n    - Dermatology referral for scar treatment later\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n26. Return in 8-12 weeks to assess response\n27. Call if severe irritation or new concerns\n28. If not responding: May add oral antibiotic or adjust regimen\n29. If severe acne develops: Dermatology referral for isotretinoin consideration\n\nPrescriptions:\n\n30. Adapalene 0.1% gel 45g - apply nightly\n31. Benzoyl peroxide 5% gel (OTC) - apply morning\n\nEducation:\n\n32. Acne treatment takes time - minimum 8-12 weeks\n33. Consistency is key - use products daily\n34. Initial worsening (purging) is normal with retinoids\n35. Don't stop when skin clears - continue maintenance\n36. Picking worsens scarring - hands off!"
