        "input": "55yo M presents knee pain OA. chronic. NSAIDs limited help. injection options discussed. \u0394 knee osteoarthritis injection options",
        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 55-year-old male with bilateral knee osteoarthritis, right worse than left, for 5 years. Right knee pain 6/10, worse with stairs, walking, and prolonged standing. Morning stiffness 20-30 minutes, then loosens up. Grinding/crepitus with movement. Occasional swelling after activity. No locking or giving way. Has tried multiple treatments with limited relief. Wants to discuss injection options. Not ready for knee replacement. Wants to remain active.\n\nPrevious Treatments:\n- Acetaminophen: Minimal relief\n- NSAIDs (ibuprofen, naproxen): Moderate relief but GI upset limits use\n- Glucosamine/chondroitin: Tried 6 months, no benefit\n- Physical therapy: Helped somewhat, completed 8 weeks\n- Knee brace: Uses occasionally\n- Weight loss: Lost 15 lbs (still overweight)\n\nPast Medical History:\n- Knee osteoarthritis\n- GERD (limits NSAID use)\n- Hypertension\n- Obesity (BMI 30)\n\nMedications:\n- Omeprazole 20 mg daily\n- Lisinopril 10 mg daily\n- Acetaminophen PRN\n\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Retired, plays golf, wants to stay active\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs: BP 128/78, Weight 210 lbs, Height 5'10\", BMI 30.1\n\nRight Knee Examination:\n- Inspection: Mild varus alignment, no effusion today\n- Palpation: Medial joint line tenderness\n- ROM: 0-125\u00b0 (mild limitation)\n- Crepitus: Present with flexion/extension\n- Ligaments: Stable (ACL, MCL, LCL, PCL intact)\n- Meniscal tests: McMurray equivocal\n- Gait: Mildly antalgic favoring right\n\nLeft Knee: Mild crepitus, less symptomatic\n\nX-ray (done 6 months ago):\n- Right knee: Kellgren-Lawrence Grade 3 (moderate-severe OA)\n  - Medial compartment narrowing\n  - Osteophytes\n  - Subchondral sclerosis\n- Left knee: Kellgren-Lawrence Grade 2 (mild-moderate OA)\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Primary Bilateral Knee Osteoarthritis, Right Greater Than Left (ICD-10: M17.0, M17.11)\n\n- Moderate-severe OA (K-L Grade 3 right)\n- Failed conservative management (NSAID-intolerant due to GERD)\n- Candidate for intra-articular injections\n- Not candidate for surgery currently (wants to defer)\n\n### Plan\nDiscussion of Injection Options:\n\n1. **Corticosteroid Injection:**\n   - Triamcinolone 40 mg or methylprednisolone 40 mg\n   - Expected response: 50-70% improve, relief lasts 4-12 weeks typically\n   - Advantages: Quick onset (days), covered by insurance, inexpensive\n   - Disadvantages: Temporary, repeated injections may accelerate cartilage loss, limit to 3-4 per year\n   - Best for: Acute flares, significant inflammation/effusion\n\n2. **Hyaluronic Acid (Viscosupplementation):**\n   - Options: Synvisc, Euflexxa, Supartz, Gel-One\n   - Mechanism: Lubricates joint, may reduce inflammation\n   - Administration: Single injection (Gel-One) or series of 3-5 weekly injections\n   - Expected response: Variable, 50-60% respond, relief lasts 3-6 months\n   - Advantages: Longer duration than corticosteroid, no cartilage harm\n   - Disadvantages: Expensive, insurance may not cover, controversial evidence (some studies show marginal benefit vs placebo)\n   - Best for: Mild-moderate OA, younger patients\n\n3. **Platelet-Rich Plasma (PRP):**\n   - Patient's own blood, concentrated platelets\n   - Mechanism: Growth factors promote tissue healing\n   - Evidence: Mixed, some studies show benefit for OA, not definitive\n   - Cost: $500-1500 per injection, typically NOT covered by insurance\n   - May need 1-3 injections, 2-4 weeks apart\n   - Best for: Mild-moderate OA, motivated patients\n\n4. **Comparison Table:**\n\n   | Feature | Corticosteroid | Hyaluronic Acid | PRP |\n   |---------|----------------|-----------------|-----|\n   | Onset | Days | Weeks | Weeks-months |\n   | Duration | Weeks-months | Months | Months |\n   | Evidence | Strong | Moderate | Emerging |\n   | Cost | Low | Moderate-High | High |\n   | Insurance | Yes | Variable | Usually No |\n\nRecommendation:\n\n5. Start with corticosteroid injection today for symptomatic relief\n   - Given current symptoms and need for relief\n   - Quick acting, covered by insurance\n6. If repeated steroid injections needed, consider viscosupplementation as alternative\n7. PRP: Discuss if interested, but cost and evidence limitations\n\nProcedure Today:\n\n8. Corticosteroid injection right knee\n   - Medication: Triamcinolone 40 mg + 4 mL 1% lidocaine\n   - Approach: Lateral suprapatellar or anterolateral\n   - Aseptic technique\n9. Post-injection:\n   - May have temporary increase in pain 24-48 hours (steroid flare)\n   - Ice PRN\n   - Rest from strenuous activity 24-48 hours\n   - Effect takes 2-7 days\n\nOngoing Management:\n\n10. Weight loss: Continue efforts - every pound lost = 4 lbs reduced stress on knee\n11. Exercise:\n    - Low-impact: Swimming, cycling, elliptical\n    - Strengthen quadriceps (critical for OA)\n    - Avoid high-impact (running, jumping)\n12. Physical therapy: Consider refresher course or home program\n13. Acetaminophen: Continue PRN (max 3g/day)\n14. Topical NSAIDs: Diclofenac gel (Voltaren) - apply to knee TID\n    - Safer than oral NSAIDs with GERD\n15. Knee sleeve/brace for support during activity\n\nGolf:\n\n16. Can continue golfing\n17. Use golf cart\n18. Proper warm-up and stretching\n19. Low-impact, good for maintaining activity\n\nSurgery Discussion:\n\n20. Eventually may need total knee replacement if conservative measures fail\n21. Current Grade 3 OA - will likely progress\n22. Average age for TKA is 65-70 - patient is 55\n23. Goal: Delay surgery as long as reasonably possible while maintaining quality of life\n24. Orthopedic referral when ready to discuss surgical options\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n25. Return in 6-8 weeks to assess response\n26. If good relief: Can repeat injection every 3-4 months as needed (max 3-4/year)\n27. If poor response: Consider viscosupplementation or MRI to evaluate for other pathology\n28. Referral to orthopedics when conservative measures no longer adequate\n\nPatient Education:\n\n29. OA is progressive but manageable\n30. Weight loss and exercise are most important long-term strategies\n31. Injections are temporizing - not curative\n32. Eventually may need surgery, but can be deferred with conservative care\n33. Goal: Stay active, manage symptoms, maintain function"
