        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 19-year-old male presenting to ED with left shoulder pain after football injury 1 hour ago. Was tackled while arm was in abduction and external rotation. Felt shoulder \"pop out.\" Immediate severe pain, unable to move arm since. Holding arm close to body. No numbness or tingling in arm. First episode - no prior shoulder dislocations. Dominant hand: Right.\n\nMechanism: Forced abduction + external rotation (classic mechanism for anterior dislocation)\n\nPast Medical History: None\nMedications: None\nAllergies: No known drug allergies\nSurgical History: None\nSocial: College student, plays college football (linebacker)\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs:\n- Blood Pressure: 135/85 mmHg (elevated, pain)\n- Heart Rate: 95 bpm (tachycardic, pain)\n- Temperature: 98.6\u00b0F\n\nPhysical Examination:\nLeft Shoulder:\n- Inspection:\n  - Arm held in adduction and internal rotation (position of comfort)\n  - Loss of normal deltoid contour (squared-off appearance)\n  - Anterior fullness (humeral head palpable anteriorly)\n  - Posterior void visible (empty glenoid)\n  - No open wound\n- Palpation:\n  - Humeral head palpable anteriorly (in subcoracoid position)\n  - Acromion prominent\n  - Severe tenderness\n  - Muscle spasm\n- Range of Motion:\n  - Unable to move shoulder actively\n  - Does not allow passive motion (muscle guarding)\n- Sulcus Sign: Deferred (acute dislocation)\n\nNeurovascular Examination (Critical):\n- Axillary Nerve (Most commonly injured):\n  - Motor: Unable to test deltoid (pain) - will recheck post-reduction\n  - Sensory: Sensation INTACT over lateral deltoid (\"regimental badge\" area)\n- Musculocutaneous Nerve:\n  - Sensation intact lateral forearm\n- Radial Nerve: Intact (wrist extension, sensation dorsal hand)\n- Median Nerve: Intact (finger flexion, sensation)\n- Ulnar Nerve: Intact (finger abduction, sensation)\n- Pulses: Radial pulse 2+, capillary refill <2 seconds\n\nRight Shoulder: Normal, full ROM, stable\n\nImaging:\n- X-ray Left Shoulder (AP, Scapular Y, Axillary):\n  - Anterior shoulder dislocation confirmed\n  - Humeral head in subcoracoid position\n  - No associated fracture (no Hill-Sachs lesion visible, no Bankart bony defect on plain films)\n  - Greater tuberosity intact\n\n### Assessment\nPrimary Diagnosis: Anterior Glenohumeral (Shoulder) Dislocation, Left (ICD-10: S43.004A)\n\nType: Anterior (95% of shoulder dislocations are anterior)\n\nMechanism: Forced abduction, extension, and external rotation during tackle\n\nNeurovascular Status: INTACT pre-reduction\n\nAge Consideration:\n- Age 19 = HIGH risk of recurrence\n- Young athletic males have highest recurrence rate (up to 70-90% lifetime)\n- Contact sport athlete = even higher risk\n\n### Plan\nImmediate Management - Closed Reduction:\n1. Procedural sedation (preferred for muscle relaxation):\n   - Propofol sedation with monitoring, OR\n   - Ketamine sedation, OR\n   - Fentanyl + Midazolam\n2. Reduction technique options:\n   - External rotation method (gentle, low traction)\n   - Cunningham technique (patient seated, no sedation sometimes possible)\n   - Stimson technique (prone, dangling arm)\n   - Traction-countertraction (traditional)\n3. Reduction success felt as \"clunk\" of humeral head relocating\n4. If sedation not available or contraindicated: Intra-articular lidocaine injection (20 mL of 1% lidocaine) before reduction\n\nPost-Reduction:\n5. Neurovascular exam repeated IMMEDIATELY after reduction:\n   - Axillary nerve: Test deltoid strength, lateral deltoid sensation\n   - Pulses, sensation throughout\n6. Post-reduction X-rays: AP and axillary views to confirm concentric reduction\n7. ROM check: Should have improved, though will still be limited\n\nImmobilization:\n8. Sling immobilization\n9. Duration: Controversial, traditionally 3-6 weeks\n   - Recent evidence suggests shorter immobilization may be acceptable\n   - 1-3 weeks may be sufficient, early PT may not increase recurrence\n10. Position: Traditional (adduction, internal rotation) is standard\n    - External rotation bracing studied but not clearly superior\n11. Remove sling for gentle pendulum exercises after 1 week\n\nPain Management:\n12. Ice: 20 minutes every 2-3 hours for first 48-72 hours\n13. NSAIDs: Ibuprofen 600 mg TID with food x 7-10 days\n14. Acetaminophen 1000 mg q6h as adjunct\n15. Opioids: Short course if needed (Norco 5/325 q4-6h PRN x 3-5 days)\n16. Muscle relaxant: Cyclobenzaprine 10 mg TID PRN for spasm\n\nAdvanced Imaging:\n17. MRI left shoulder (after acute phase, usually 1-2 weeks):\n    - Evaluate for:\n      - Bankart lesion (anterior labral tear - common)\n      - Hill-Sachs lesion (posterior humeral head defect)\n      - Rotator cuff tear (uncommon in young patients)\n      - Other labral pathology\n18. MRI findings will guide surgical decision-making\n\nOrthopedic/Sports Medicine Follow-up:\n19. Follow-up with orthopedic surgery or sports medicine in 1-2 weeks\n20. Discuss imaging findings and surgical options\n21. Especially important given age (19) and sport (football)\n\nRecurrence Risk Counseling:\n22. YOUNG + ATHLETE + FIRST DISLOCATION = HIGH RECURRENCE RISK\n23. Recurrence rates:\n    - Age <20: Up to 70-90% lifetime recurrence with conservative treatment\n    - Age 20-30: 50-70%\n    - Age >40: 10-20%\n24. Each subsequent dislocation causes more bone loss and easier to redislocate\n25. This information important for surgical decision-making\n\nSurgical Consideration:\n26. Primary surgical repair (Bankart repair) increasingly recommended for:\n    - Young patients (<25 years)\n    - Contact sport athletes\n    - High-demand activities\n27. Evidence shows primary repair reduces recurrence rate significantly\n28. Discuss with orthopedics/sports medicine\n29. Surgical options:\n    - Arthroscopic Bankart repair (labral repair) - most common\n    - Open Bankart repair (if bone loss)\n    - Latarjet procedure (if significant bone loss)\n30. If MRI shows Bankart lesion + young athlete: Strong surgical recommendation\n\nConservative Management (If Chosen):\n31. Sling x 1-3 weeks\n32. Physical therapy starting at 1-2 weeks:\n    - Phase 1: Pendulum exercises, ROM\n    - Phase 2: Rotator cuff strengthening\n    - Phase 3: Sport-specific training\n33. Full recovery: 3-4 months\n34. Bracing for sport: Shoulder stabilizer brace\n35. Risk: High recurrence, especially with return to football\n\nReturn to Sport:\n36. Timeline depends on treatment approach:\n    - Conservative: 3-4 months (but high recurrence risk)\n    - Surgical repair: 4-6 months post-op\n37. Criteria: Full ROM, strength equal to opposite side, no apprehension, sport-specific testing\n38. Brace recommended for contact sports\n\nComplications to Monitor:\n39. Recurrent dislocation (most common, especially young athletes)\n40. Axillary nerve injury (usually neuropraxia, recovers in weeks-months)\n41. Rotator cuff tear (rare in young patients)\n42. Bone loss (cumulative with recurrent dislocations)\n43. Early arthritis (chronic instability)\n\nDischarge Instructions:\n44. Keep sling on except for exercises as instructed\n45. Ice regularly\n46. Take medications as prescribed\n47. No lifting, pushing, or reaching with left arm\n48. No sports until cleared\n49. Return immediately if:\n    - Numbness/tingling develops in arm\n    - Fingers turn blue or cold\n    - Shoulder feels like it \"pops out\" again\n    - Fever, severe swelling\n\nFollow-up:\n50. Orthopedics/Sports Medicine in 1-2 weeks\n51. Schedule MRI as recommended\n52. Athletic trainer/team physician involvement for return-to-play decisions"
