        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 45-year-old female with bilateral plantar fasciitis for 1 year, right worse than left. Reports heel pain rated 7/10 right, 5/10 left. Classic presentation: Pain with first steps in morning (takes 10-15 minutes to loosen up), improves during day, worsens after prolonged standing/walking. Pain at plantar medial heel. Works as nurse - on feet 12-hour shifts. Gained 20 lbs over past 2 years. Pain limiting exercise and affecting job performance.\n\nPrevious Treatments:\n- OTC arch supports: Minimal relief\n- Custom orthotics (6 months): Some improvement initially, less effective now\n- Stretching exercises: Inconsistent compliance\n- NSAIDs (ibuprofen): Partial relief, GI upset limits use\n- Night splint: Tried briefly, stopped due to discomfort\n- Corticosteroid injection (right heel) x2: Relief for 6-8 weeks each time, then returned\n\nPast Medical History:\n- Plantar fasciitis\n- Obesity (BMI 31)\n- No diabetes\n\nMedications: Ibuprofen 400 mg PRN\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Nurse (12-hour shifts), non-smoker, minimal exercise currently\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs: BP 126/78, Weight 185 lbs, Height 5'5\", BMI 30.8\n\nMusculoskeletal Examination:\n\nBilateral Feet:\n- Inspection: Mild pes planus (flat feet) bilaterally\n- Palpation:\n  - Right: Point tenderness at medial calcaneal tubercle (plantar fascia origin) 8/10\n  - Left: Tenderness 6/10 at same location\n  - Windlass test: Positive bilaterally (pain with passive toe dorsiflexion)\n- ROM: Ankle dorsiflexion mildly limited bilaterally (tight gastrocnemius/soleus)\n- Strength: 5/5 bilateral LE\n- Neurovascular: Intact\n- No Achilles tendon tenderness\n\nGait: Antalgic, shortened stride, walks on lateral border of feet\n\nImaging:\n- X-ray (6 months ago): Bilateral heel spurs (common finding, not cause of pain)\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Chronic Bilateral Plantar Fasciitis (ICD-10: M72.2)\n\n- 1-year duration - chronic\n- Failed conservative management: Stretching, orthotics, night splint (poor compliance), NSAIDs, corticosteroid injections (temporary relief)\n- Contributing factors: Obesity, prolonged standing (occupation), tight calves, flat feet\n\nTreatment Options Discussion:\n1. Optimized conservative care\n2. Extracorporeal shockwave therapy (ESWT)\n3. Platelet-rich plasma (PRP) injection\n4. Surgical release (last resort)\n\n### Plan\nOptimized Conservative Care:\n\n1. Stretching (MUST BE CONSISTENT):\n   - Plantar fascia stretch: 3x/day, 10 reps, hold 30 sec\n   - Gastrocnemius stretch: 3x/day, hold 30 sec each leg\n   - Soleus stretch: 3x/day, hold 30 sec\n   - Before getting out of bed in morning - stretch first\n\n2. Night splint: Retry dorsiflexion night splint\n   - Maintains stretch overnight\n   - Use consistently for 3 months\n   - Start with shorter duration if uncomfortable (2-3 hours initially)\n\n3. Orthotics: Continue custom orthotics, ensure proper fit\n   - Consider heel cups with cushioning\n   - Wear supportive shoes at all times (no barefoot, no flat shoes)\n\n4. Ice: Rolling frozen water bottle under foot 15 min after activity\n\n5. Physical therapy referral:\n   - Supervised stretching program\n   - Iontophoresis\n   - Ultrasound\n   - Manual therapy\n   - Strengthening (intrinsic foot muscles)\n\nAdvanced Treatment Options:\n\n6. Extracorporeal Shockwave Therapy (ESWT):\n   - Non-invasive, acoustic waves to heel\n   - Stimulates healing\n   - Series of 3-5 treatments\n   - 60-80% success in chronic cases\n   - Insurance coverage variable\n\n7. Platelet-Rich Plasma (PRP) Injection:\n   - Patient's own blood, concentrated platelets\n   - Inject into plantar fascia origin\n   - Promotes healing via growth factors\n   - Evidence: Moderate - may be superior to corticosteroid long-term\n   - Cost: Often not covered by insurance ($500-1500)\n   - Recovery: Avoid significant activity 2-4 weeks\n\n8. Comparison - PRP vs Corticosteroid:\n   - Corticosteroid: Quick relief but short-lived, risk of fat pad atrophy, fascia rupture with repeated injections\n   - PRP: Slower onset but potentially more durable, promotes healing vs suppressing inflammation\n\nRecommendation:\n\n9. Start with optimized conservative care:\n   - Consistent stretching (critical)\n   - Night splint retry\n   - PT for 4-6 weeks\n   - If failure: Consider ESWT or PRP\n\n10. PRP injection: Reasonable option given:\n    - Chronic symptoms (1 year)\n    - Multiple failed treatments\n    - Temporary response to steroids (not wanting repeated steroids)\n    - Can proceed if patient prefers after understanding cost and evidence\n\n11. Plan: Trial optimized conservative for 6-8 weeks, then reassess for PRP or ESWT if not improving\n\nWeight Management:\n\n12. BMI 31 - weight is significant contributor\n13. Goal: Lose 10-15% body weight (20-25 lbs)\n14. Reduces mechanical load on plantar fascia\n15. Nutrition counseling referral\n16. Low-impact exercise (swimming, cycling, upper body) while foot heals\n\nWork Modifications:\n\n17. 12-hour nursing shifts are challenging\n    - Supportive shoes with orthotics at all times\n    - Compression socks may help\n    - Take sitting breaks when possible\n    - Consider temporary work modification if available\n\nMedications:\n\n18. Topical diclofenac gel: Apply to heel 3-4x/day (avoids GI side effects)\n19. Limit oral NSAIDs due to GI upset\n20. Acetaminophen PRN for pain\n\nAvoid:\n\n21. No repeated corticosteroid injections (already had 2)\n    - Risk of fat pad atrophy, fascia rupture increases\n22. No barefoot walking\n23. Avoid high-impact activity until resolved\n\nSurgery (Last Resort):\n\n24. Plantar fascia release surgery:\n    - Only if failed all conservative measures for 6-12 months\n    - 70-90% success but risk of complications\n    - Not indicated currently\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n25. PT: 2x/week for 4-6 weeks\n26. PM&R: 6-8 weeks to reassess\n27. If not improving: Schedule for PRP or ESWT\n\nPatient Education:\n\n28. Plantar fasciitis is self-limiting in most cases (12-18 months)\n29. Consistent stretching is the most important intervention\n30. Weight loss will significantly help\n31. Patience required - chronic cases take longer to heal"
