        "output": "### Subjective\nPatient is a 32-year-old female presenting with PTSD symptoms following severe motor vehicle accident 1 year ago. She was a passenger, car was T-boned, she was trapped for 30 minutes, witnessed driver (friend) seriously injured. Has since experienced:\n\n- Intrusions: Recurrent nightmares 3-4x/week about accident, flashbacks triggered by sirens, driving through intersections. Feels like she's reliving it.\n- Avoidance: Avoids driving (hasn't driven in 1 year), avoids intersections as passenger, avoids car-related movies/news\n- Negative alterations: Guilt (\"I should have warned her\"), emotional numbing, detachment from friends, loss of interest in activities\n- Hyperarousal: Hypervigilant as passenger, exaggerated startle, difficulty falling asleep, irritability, difficulty concentrating\n\nSymptoms started within month of accident, persistent. Affecting work (late due to relying on others for rides), relationships (withdrew from friends), and quality of life. No prior trauma history.\n\nPast Medical History: None\nPast Psychiatric History: None\nMedications: None\nAllergies: NKDA\nSocial: Teacher, single, non-smoker, rare alcohol\n\n### Objective\nVital Signs: BP 122/78, HR 76\n\nGeneral: Anxious, tearful when discussing accident\n\nMental Status Exam:\n- Appearance: Well-groomed, appropriately dressed\n- Behavior: Restless, tearful, avoids eye contact when discussing trauma\n- Speech: Normal rate, slightly tremulous\n- Mood: \"Anxious, on edge\"\n- Affect: Anxious, tearful, constricted\n- Thought Process: Linear, goal-directed\n- Thought Content: Intrusive trauma memories, no SI/HI, no psychosis\n- Cognition: Intact but reports concentration difficulty\n- Insight/Judgment: Good\n\nScales:\n- PCL-5 (PTSD Checklist): 52 (probable PTSD, cutoff 31-33)\n- PHQ-9: 12 (moderate depression, likely secondary)\n- GAD-7: 14 (moderate anxiety)\n\n### Assessment\nDiagnosis: Posttraumatic Stress Disorder (ICD-10: F43.10)\n\nDSM-5 Criteria Met:\n- Criterion A: Exposure to traumatic event (MVA, threat of death) \u2713\n- Criterion B: Intrusion symptoms (nightmares, flashbacks) \u2713\n- Criterion C: Avoidance (driving, intersections) \u2713\n- Criterion D: Negative alterations (guilt, numbing, detachment) \u2713\n- Criterion E: Hyperarousal (hypervigilance, startle, insomnia) \u2713\n- Duration >1 month \u2713\n- Functional impairment \u2713\n\nSecondary: Depressive symptoms (likely secondary to PTSD)\n\n### Plan\nPsychotherapy (First-Line for PTSD):\n\n1. Trauma-focused psychotherapy - ESSENTIAL\n2. Options (all evidence-based for PTSD):\n   - Prolonged Exposure (PE): Gold standard, confronting trauma memories systematically\n   - Cognitive Processing Therapy (CPT): Addresses maladaptive beliefs about trauma\n   - EMDR (Eye Movement Desensitization and Reprocessing): Effective alternative\n\n3. Referral to therapist trained in trauma-focused therapy\n4. Weekly sessions, 12-16 sessions typical\n\nPharmacotherapy:\n\n5. First-line: SSRI or SNRI\n   - Start: Sertraline 25 mg daily, increase to 50 mg after 1 week\n   - Target dose: 100-200 mg/day for PTSD\n   - FDA-approved for PTSD\n   - Helps all symptom clusters\n\n6. Alternative: Paroxetine (FDA-approved for PTSD), venlafaxine (SNRI)\n\n7. For nightmares specifically:\n   - Prazosin 1 mg at bedtime, titrate up to 6-15 mg\n   - Alpha-1 blocker, reduces trauma-related nightmares\n   - Monitor for orthostatic hypotension\n   - Starting: Prazosin 1 mg at bedtime\n\nMedication Plan:\n- Sertraline 25 mg \u2192 50 mg after 1 week \u2192 titrate to 100-200 mg\n- Prazosin 1 mg at bedtime \u2192 increase by 1 mg every 3-7 days as tolerated to 3-6 mg\n\nSleep:\n\n8. Sleep hygiene counseling\n9. Regular sleep schedule\n10. Avoid screens before bed\n11. Prazosin will help trauma-related sleep disruption\n12. Avoid benzodiazepines and sleep aids (can worsen PTSD)\n\nAvoidance Behaviors:\n\n13. Avoidance maintains PTSD - key target of treatment\n14. Gradual exposure will be part of therapy\n15. For now, use relaxation techniques when distressed\n16. Don't force exposures before therapy starts\n\nCoping Strategies:\n\n17. Grounding techniques for flashbacks:\n    - 5-4-3-2-1 (5 things you see, 4 hear, 3 touch, 2 smell, 1 taste)\n    - Focus on present moment\n18. Deep breathing exercises\n19. Mindfulness apps (Calm, Headspace)\n20. Social support - reconnect with safe people\n\nAvoid:\n\n21. Benzodiazepines - NOT recommended for PTSD (can worsen outcomes, impair exposure therapy)\n22. Alcohol/substances (common self-medication, worsens PTSD)\n\nWork/Function:\n\n23. May need temporary accommodations (flexible schedule)\n24. Therapy is intensive - prioritize it\n25. Function should improve with treatment\n\nSafety:\n\n26. No SI currently - monitor\n27. Crisis resources: 988 Suicide & Crisis Lifeline\n28. Veterans Crisis Line if applicable\n\nFollow-Up:\n\n29. Return in 2 weeks to assess medication tolerance\n30. Therapy intake ASAP\n31. Titrate sertraline and prazosin as tolerated\n32. Call if worsening symptoms or SI\n\nPatient Education:\n\n33. PTSD is treatable\n34. Therapy is key - medication supports but therapy creates lasting change\n35. Symptoms may temporarily worsen during trauma processing (expected)\n36. Recovery is possible - many achieve significant improvement or remission"
